WEBVTT

01:06.501 --> 01:11.506
Graffiti is special because
when you do art in your room,

01:11.549 --> 01:16.772
in your home, it's just for you,
and sometimes you make a show,

01:16.815 --> 01:19.905
exhibitions so more
people see it.

01:19.949 --> 01:22.386
But when you do in the street,

01:22.430 --> 01:24.736
you are communicating
with everybody.

01:30.090 --> 01:31.700
The first time
I started listening

01:31.743 --> 01:34.442
to hip-hop music,
I definitely just
liked it.

01:36.357 --> 01:39.969
The message was quite
very strong about how
people were suffering.

01:40.012 --> 01:42.276
And automatically,
I just said to myself,

01:42.319 --> 01:45.627
"This is exactly the kind
of music that can fit
what I'm living."

01:51.676 --> 01:55.506
The reason I love
fashion is because of
empowering women.

01:55.550 --> 01:57.247
They make the shirt,
and they're proud,

01:57.291 --> 01:59.902
and it's also something that
you can teach a lot of people.

01:59.945 --> 02:02.252
I mean, it's a skill
that anyone can learn,

02:02.296 --> 02:04.124
I think, if they put
their mind to it.

02:05.777 --> 02:07.562
I believe in women so much,

02:07.605 --> 02:09.955
and I know that they have
so much strength and courage.

02:09.999 --> 02:12.306
And I love to maximize
their potential

02:12.349 --> 02:14.395
because I know that
they have the potential.

02:20.966 --> 02:22.925
In sex trafficking
and violence,

02:22.968 --> 02:25.710
bodies are very,
very important factor.

02:25.754 --> 02:28.148
Most of the time when
the violence happen,

02:28.191 --> 02:31.020
somebody else is
controlling the body.

02:31.063 --> 02:33.718
When I'm
doing the dance
and movement,

02:33.762 --> 02:35.590
I am the controller
of the body.

02:35.633 --> 02:40.116
I am liberating myself,
and that physical experience,

02:40.160 --> 02:43.554
that this is my body,
bring an empowerment.

02:58.700 --> 03:01.224
Women-- angry about
economic, social,

03:01.268 --> 03:04.053
and political inequality
between the sexes--

03:04.096 --> 03:06.011
took their fight
to the streets.

03:06.055 --> 03:07.926
First of all, our bottom line is

03:07.970 --> 03:10.407
we assume that women
are equal human beings.

03:10.451 --> 03:12.061
We're not still
arguing about it.

03:12.104 --> 03:14.585
Human rights are
women's rights,

03:14.629 --> 03:17.371
and women's rights
are human rights

03:17.414 --> 03:19.895
once and for all.

03:19.938 --> 03:23.942
Study after study shows
that investing in women's
leadership and development

03:23.986 --> 03:27.163
is one of the smartest
investments societies can make.

03:27.207 --> 03:30.166
Treating women
as second-class citizens

03:30.210 --> 03:33.169
is a bad tradition.
It holds you back.

03:33.213 --> 03:36.172
Even though we have made
so much progress,

03:36.216 --> 03:39.088
there are stereotypes
and prejudices

03:39.131 --> 03:42.700
about women that are
just refusing to go away.

03:42.744 --> 03:44.267
But what about the
women's revolution?

03:44.311 --> 03:45.921
I think we're stalled.

03:45.964 --> 03:47.531
You think about
how far we've come,

03:47.575 --> 03:50.273
and it seems like, "Okay,
the problem's gotten worse."

03:50.317 --> 03:53.755
A shocking
and disturbing video
appears on social media

03:53.798 --> 03:56.366
of more than 30 men
allegedly gang-raping

03:56.410 --> 03:58.760
a 16-year-old girl
in Rio de Janeiro.

03:58.803 --> 04:02.111
200 teenage
girls were abducted by
heavily-armed men.

04:02.154 --> 04:03.852
23-year-old woman
in New Delhi

04:03.895 --> 04:06.768
was brutally
gang-raped on a bus.

04:06.811 --> 04:10.380
Malala Yousafzai,
a 14-year-old advocate
for girl's education,

04:10.424 --> 04:12.948
was targeted and shot
on her school bus.

04:12.991 --> 04:14.515
So if the problem's
gotten worse,

04:14.558 --> 04:16.299
clearly these strategies

04:16.343 --> 04:18.519
that we've been employing
have not been working.

04:18.562 --> 04:20.956
So we need to think
outside the box,

04:20.999 --> 04:24.307
we need to try those sort of
innovative, creative solutions.

04:24.351 --> 04:30.313
Art is one medium through
which you can address issues.

04:30.357 --> 04:34.535
We all appreciate a good song,
a beautiful painting.

04:34.578 --> 04:37.451
So the music of
art is universal.

04:58.689 --> 05:02.214
During the concert,
we get everybody out.

05:02.258 --> 05:05.261
And then from there,
you just give them information.

05:05.305 --> 05:07.437
And we gonna use
our music to put

05:07.481 --> 05:09.961
very strong messages
inside to give it to them.

05:10.005 --> 05:12.007
They will dance,
and they will learn.

05:30.025 --> 05:31.853
Okay, not bad. We go.

05:31.896 --> 05:35.683
When I started to make hip-hop,
I was not an activist.

05:35.726 --> 05:39.121
And it's only when I moved
from Dakar to Germany,

05:39.164 --> 05:43.952
I think I started to do
some kind of activism
to say I can use my voice

05:43.995 --> 05:47.303
for those one who doesn't have
the possibility to do so.

05:47.347 --> 05:50.306
We say good morning, Sista Fa.
Very nice to see you.

05:50.350 --> 05:51.873
Sister Fa is not a nun.

05:51.916 --> 05:53.788
She is, in fact, an award-winning

05:53.831 --> 05:57.095
Senegalese urban, soul, and
hip-hop star, and activist.

05:57.139 --> 06:00.185
Fatou Diatta, known
by her stage name, Sister Fa.

06:00.229 --> 06:03.754
She is breaking taboos by
returning to her home country

06:03.798 --> 06:06.322
to talk about this issue.
She joins me now.

06:06.366 --> 06:07.802
Thank you so much
for being with us,

06:07.845 --> 06:10.282
and thank you for
the really great work

06:10.326 --> 06:12.067
that you're doing around...

06:30.651 --> 06:32.435
I can say yes, but it's
just like the one behind
this one here.

06:36.047 --> 06:37.658
Yeah, this is your
family that you grew up with?

06:37.701 --> 06:38.702
Yes.

06:50.845 --> 06:51.846
Definitely

07:16.087 --> 07:21.615
I was the first girl who was
doing hip-hop as a singer.

07:21.658 --> 07:24.008
Then I was just fighting,
because in Senegal,

07:24.052 --> 07:26.968
it was not easy for a woman
to be in the hip-hop movement.

07:27.011 --> 07:30.275
We had no place,
because I think the producer,

07:30.319 --> 07:34.279
those people were, like, more
into how they can make money.

07:34.323 --> 07:38.370
With a lady, if she get married
and have children, it's over.

07:38.414 --> 07:41.722
And I did not even
wait for someone to
produce my first CD.

07:41.765 --> 07:43.375
I did it by my own.

07:43.419 --> 07:44.986
Yes.

07:51.514 --> 07:54.125
In Brazil,
people love graffiti.

07:54.169 --> 07:56.650
Grafitti is everywhere--
in the TV, newspaper,

07:56.693 --> 07:59.740
magazine. It's art. It's nice.

07:59.783 --> 08:02.786
They don't, like, call
the cops to arrest you

08:02.830 --> 08:05.267
because you're doing
graffiti. They like it.

08:05.310 --> 08:07.748
They're probably gonna
offer you water or coffee,

08:07.791 --> 08:10.098
ask if you need some paint

08:10.141 --> 08:12.666
to finish your wall.
It's incredible.

08:56.274 --> 08:59.364
And I think what's
happened to me is...

08:59.408 --> 09:05.762
I didn't want to accept
the position, to be a
girlfriend of the boy.

09:06.850 --> 09:11.376
The graffiti scene is
like... really for men.

09:11.420 --> 09:14.423
It's hard to be a girl inside
of the graffiti world,

09:14.466 --> 09:16.164
but she's doing really well.

09:19.080 --> 09:21.386
It doesn't matter
what you wanna say,

09:21.430 --> 09:23.388
if you go to the street
and write something,

09:23.432 --> 09:24.781
people are gonna read it,

09:24.825 --> 09:27.654
like a little kid, old guy,
a poor, a rich people--

09:27.697 --> 09:29.090
everybody's gonna see.

09:29.133 --> 09:31.962
You know it's like,
uh, democratic art.

09:53.680 --> 09:56.117
We have to look a lot
at what James Scott,

09:56.160 --> 09:58.249
an anthropologist, calls
"the weapons of the weak."

09:59.120 --> 10:00.948
All right, these are
weapons that people,

10:00.991 --> 10:05.256
who have no formal
political power, can employ.

10:05.300 --> 10:09.086
And in Brazil, of course,
the weapons of the weak have
always been the weapons

10:09.130 --> 10:11.785
of the popular classes,
the lower classes,

10:11.828 --> 10:15.353
and they've been things
like samba, music, humor.

10:15.397 --> 10:17.878
And graffiti fits
right in there.

10:57.178 --> 11:00.790
I love dancing like I love art.

11:00.834 --> 11:05.534
Any kind of dance,
poetry, music,

11:05.577 --> 11:07.884
but I'm passionate with
the dance from my childhood.

11:07.928 --> 11:12.715
I never attracted with
the stage performances.

11:12.759 --> 11:19.156
I love dance for self dancing,
and choreography,

11:19.200 --> 11:22.812
and how I can use
dance differently.

11:38.959 --> 11:42.963
I saw a poster
in 1996 with a poem.

11:57.238 --> 11:59.588
It was an
anti-trafficking poster,

11:59.631 --> 12:06.290
with a girl's face,
and I thought, "Yes,
this is my path."

12:08.162 --> 12:12.122
So, she learned about that and
immediately went to Sanlap,

12:12.166 --> 12:15.909
who was the organization that
she first started working with,

12:15.952 --> 12:19.216
and they were really
rescuing girls from brothels,

12:19.260 --> 12:21.523
helping them become survivors.

12:21.566 --> 12:24.526
And immediately
in working with them
and volunteering there,

12:24.569 --> 12:28.617
she began to recognize
that the way in which they
were treating these girls

12:28.660 --> 12:31.402
